        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Solver must be a commercially available code with published verification test suite documentation. Project-level SQA must include version control of input files and documented regression testing. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Code verification confirmed through comparison of solver results against three analytical solutions: Poiseuille flow in a straight tube (error < 0.1%), lid-driven cavity at Re=1000 (velocity profiles match Ghia et al. benchmark within 0.5%), and rotating disk flow (Ekman layer thickness within 1.2%). All tests executed with the solver version used for production runs.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ncv-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Solver must be verified against at least two analytical or manufactured solutions relevant to the physics of interest. Errors must be within expected truncation-error bounds. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed on three systematically refined meshes (coarse: 4.2M cells, medium: 11.8M cells, fine: 31.5M cells; refinement ratio ~1.41). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. 2008 procedure. Fine-mesh GCI < 2.8% for volume-averaged shear stress (primary hemolysis driver) and < 1.9% for pressure head. Observed order of convergence p=1.87, consistent with second-order spatial discretization. Exceeds Gradation 2 requirement; achieves Gradation 3.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/disc-error-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "GCI on quantities of interest must be reported using at least three mesh levels with systematic refinement ratio. GCI < 5% on primary QoI required. Gradation 2 minimum; Gradation 3 achieved here through formal Richardson extrapolation."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions documented in FDA pump benchmark protocol and project-specific hemolysis test plan. Flow rates measured with Coriolis mass flowmeter (±0.5% FS), rotational speed via optical tachometer (±1 RPM), temperature controlled to 36 ± 0.5 °C, and hematocrit verified by microcentrifuge before each test run. All boundary conditions applied in CFD match measured experimental inlet/outlet conditions within measurement uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions must be documented with calibrated instrumentation. CFD boundary conditions must match experimental values within stated measurement uncertainty. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using area-weighted RMS error metric for velocity fields and percent error for RHI scalar. Validation metric computed per ASME V&V 20-2009 framework. All comparison metrics documented in validation report VR-CPB-2025-001. Systematic and random components of model error separated; no evidence of systematic bias exceeding 5% in primary QoI.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison metric must be defined a priori and computed for all validation cases. Metric must account for experimental uncertainty. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — relative hemolysis index (RHI) computed from the Giersiepen power-law damage integral over Lagrangian particle trajectories — is directly linked to the regulatory decision criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate device). Secondary QoIs (volume-averaged shear stress, pressure-flow characteristic) are mechanistically connected to RHI through the hemolysis model. QoI relevance matrix documented and reviewed by clinical engineering team.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Primary QoI must be demonstrably linked to the clinical or regulatory decision criterion. Mechanistic connection between computational output and device performance endpoint must be documented. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which shares impeller diameter, blade count, and volute proportions with the device under assessment. Operating points span the clinical CPB envelope (2–7 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Blood analog fluid (40% glycerol-water, viscosity matched to blood at 37 °C) used in PIV experiments; hemolysis tests performed with fresh ovine blood. Relevance gaps (Newtonian approximation, animal blood) documented and bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/val-relevance-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criterion — MRL 2",
        "description": "Validation geometry and operating conditions must be sufficiently similar to the COU that extrapolation uncertainty is bounded and documented. Any relevance gaps must be identified and their impact on QoI assessed. Gradation 2 or higher required."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU because the commercial solver (ANSYS Fluent) has an extensive published verification test suite and the code verification factor (above) addresses solver correctness at the level required. Separate solver error quantification beyond code verification is not required at Gradation 2 for MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 4. This scoping decision is documented in the project credibility plan CP-CPB-2025-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 because the simulation team consists of two PhD-level CFD engineers with >5 years of blood pump simulation experience, and all simulation inputs were independently reviewed by a second analyst prior to production runs. The software quality assurance factor captures procedural controls sufficient at MRL 2. Formal use-error quantification is reserved for MRL 3 and above per project credibility plan CP-CPB-2025-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (turbulence model selection, Newtonian vs. non-Newtonian blood rheology) is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The k-omega SST turbulence model is the de facto standard for rotating machinery hemolysis CFD and its adequacy for this geometry class is supported by published literature (Fraser et al. 2011, Hariharan et al. 2011). Newtonian approximation error at CPB shear rates (>100 s-1) is bounded by sensitivity analysis documented in the validation report. Formal model form factor assessment is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Formal model inputs uncertainty quantification is scoped out at MRL 2. All material properties (blood density, viscosity at 37 °C) and boundary condition values are sourced from calibrated instrumentation with documented uncertainty. The discretization error and test conditions factors capture input-related uncertainty at the level required for MRL 2. Full probabilistic input uncertainty propagation is reserved for MRL 3 per project credibility plan CP-CPB-2025-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization (blood donor variability, hematocrit distribution) is scoped out at MRL 2 because hemolysis experiments used pooled ovine blood with hematocrit controlled to 40 ± 2% and the acceptance criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate) is inherently comparative, reducing sensitivity to absolute sample variability. Sample-to-sample variability was assessed informally via triplicate runs at the worst-case operating point; CV < 6% observed. Formal test sample factor is not required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between validation experiments and the COU is scoped out as a separate factor at MRL 2 because the relevance of validation activities factor (assessed above) addresses the mapping between experimental and COU conditions. The operating envelope and applicability constraint objects formally bound the domain of equivalency. Separate equivalency factor assessment is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 4 and project credibility plan CP-CPB-2025-001."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-hemolysis-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The UnitOfAssurance is accepted as providing sufficient credibility evidence to support the regulatory submission claim that the CFD model correctly identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device. All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels at MRL 2: Software QA (2/2), Numerical Code Verification (2/2), Discretization Error (3/2, exceeds requirement), Test Conditions (2/2), Output Comparison (2/2), QoI Relevance (2/2), and Validation Relevance (2/2). Six factors are formally scoped out with documented rationale consistent with MRL 2 requirements per ASME V&V 40-2018. Three independent validation datasets support the hemolysis prediction capability: FDA benchmark PIV data, project-specific RHI in-vitro data, and geometry tolerance sweep data. Uncertainty quantification is documented for all three validation results, with 95th-percentile RHI remaining below 0.85 across the operating envelope, preserving a 0.15-unit margin to the RH < 1 acceptance criterion after uncertainty addition. The sensitivity analysis (hasSensitivityAnalysis: true) covering turbulence model variant and hemolysis power-law exponent perturbation confirms that the worst-case identification is robust to plausible model form and parameter uncertainties. No credibility shortfalls requiring offset rationale are present. The evidence chain is complete from foundational experimental datasets through validation activities to this assurance package.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
